<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note9" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Antony*.html#ref9
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">9</A>
That is <I>ten times</I> 100,000 sesterces, or 250,000 denarii. For the Roman denarius Plutarch regularly uses the nearly equivalent Greek drachma (which had about the value of the French franc).

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
	<P CLASS="b0 a0">
Thayer's Note: The French franc pops up unexpectedly here, because in 1914 when this volume of Plutarch was translated France was still a world power, and her currency was the standard measure of worth, much like the dollar today. Thruout the 20c the value of the franc fell almost continuously to a fraction of its then value, despite being artificially multiplied by 100 in the late 1950's, and has now been replaced by the euro: the translator's note has thus itself fallen into the realm of historical obscurity.
	</DIV>


