	<HR CLASS="endnotes"><A ID="endnotes_T"></A>
	<H2>
Thayer's Notes:
	</H2>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:torturing_slaves" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Antony*.html#ref:torturing_slaves
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">a</A>
To the modern reader, this sounds like some kind of cruel personal vindictiveness. The ancient reader knew otherwise: putting slaves to the torture — which, from a practical standpoint, often meant merely threatening them with torture — was the standard way of interrogating them. For further details, see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Judex.html#evidence
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,SmithSub1,WIDTH,SmithSubWidth1)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
this passage of the article <SPAN CLASS="smallcaps">Judex</SPAN>
	</A>
of Smith's <I>Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</I>, as well as the brief article
	<A CLASS="smallcaps" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Tormentum2.html
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Smith1,WIDTH,SmithWidth1)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Tormentum</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="a0 justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:Octavius" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Antony*.html#ref:Octavius
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">b</A>
The Greek, as given on the facing page of the Loeb edition, is <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">Ὀκταουϊανóν</SPAN> = 'Octavianus'; and the <SPAN CLASS="source">Octavius</SPAN> in chapters <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Antony*.html#19
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">19
	</A>
and <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Antony*.html#30
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">30
	</A>
correspond to no Greek at all, but were supplied by the translator, apparently to make it quite clear who Plutarch is talking about.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:Xuthus" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Antony*.html#ref:Xuthus
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">c</A>
For the correction, I am indebted to Prof. John Morgan who looked at the Loeb edition's own facing Greek text and found <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">Ξοῦθοι</SPAN>, as I find in my copy as well.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:Antiphon" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Antony*.html#ref:Antiphon
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">d</A>
The life and works of Antiphon are very thoroughly treated in
	<A HREF="
https://elfinspell.com/ClassicalTexts/Dobson-TheGreekOrators/Chapter2-Antiphon.html
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Dobson's <I>Greek Orators</I>, chapter <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN></A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:Antony_losing_even_at_quail_fighting" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Antony*.html#ref:Antony_losing_even_at_quail_fighting
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">e</A>
Plutarch repeats the story in
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Fortuna_Romanorum*.html#T319f
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>On the Fortune of the Romans</I>, 319<SPAN CLASS="small">F</SPAN></A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:Syrian_language" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Antony*.html#ref:Syrian_language
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">f</A>
Greek and Roman authors often write "Syrian" to mean "Assyrian" (<SPAN CLASS="whole">neo-Assyrian</SPAN> cuneiform remained the script of official documents until Roman times) or, as here, probably, "Aramaic" — the spoken language current in the old Assyrian Empire since well before Alexander. At this point, Antony was still in Media, which lies to the east of the Assyrian heartland, bordering on the Caspian Sea; Syria, on the other hand, lies to the west.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="a0 justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:taxation" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Antony*.html#ref:taxation
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">g</A><!--TAXATION-->
Some things were better in Antiquity than in our time, and this is one of them. That a rate of taxation which in the United States at least would be rather low and is exacted of us yearly, should in ancient Rome have been considered a one-shot extortionate scheme — on top of which today we can add an endless stream of sales taxes, property taxes, "user's fees" on <SPAN CLASS="whole">quasi-state</SPAN> monopolies, wealth taxes and so forth —, is a monument to the ingenuity, spending habits, and rapaciousness of modern bureaucrats and the labor unions that live off them, as well as to the sheep-like temperament we have been bribed by the proponents of the Welfare State into developing over the last hundred years. Government will give us lots of stuff with our own money, and charge us an additional cut to do so: what to us is normalcy would have struck the Romans as a perversion.
	<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
For further confirmation of this in ancient authors, see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cassius_Dio/55*.html#25.5
	"TARGET="Cassius_Dio_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Dio,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Cassius Dio, <SPAN CLASS="small">LV</SPAN>.25
	</A>
(and my note);
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Appian/Civil_Wars/4*.html#34.3
	"TARGET="Appian_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Appian,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Appian, B. C. <SPAN CLASS="small">IV</SPAN>.34
	</A>
(and my note);
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Augustus/Res_Gestae/3*.html#note67
	"TARGET="Augustus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,ResGestae)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
the Loeb edition note on Augustus, Res Gestae, <SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN>.17</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:the_image_of_Cleopatra" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Antony*.html#ref:the_image_of_Cleopatra
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">h</A>
It appears just marginally possible that this portrait still exists. For the fascinating details, see
	<A HREF="
https://penelope.uchicago.edu/pseudodoxia/pseudo512.html
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Of the Picture of Cleopatra</I>
	</A>
in Sir Thomas Browne's <I>Pseudodoxia Epidemica</I>, with a comprehensive bit of sleuthing by the website author, in which he tracks the portrait thru the early 19th century, when it appears to have vanished altogether — a fitting <I>objet</I> for Browne's own <I>Musaeum Clausum</I>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:Caligula_reigning_with_distinction" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Antony*.html#ref:Caligula_reigning_with_distinction
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">i</A>
In Greek, <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">ἐπιφανῶς</SPAN>. Plutarch is speaking of Caligula.



